05174nam a22008535i 9780813539300DE-B159720230127011820.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230127t20062006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135393007 a10.36019/97808135393002doi  a(DE-B1597)528948  a(OCoLC)744987199  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR9080.5b.K38 2006 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a820.9/9287/091712411 aKatrak, Ketu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of the Female Body :bPostcolonial Women Writers /cKetu Katrak. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- t1. Theorizing a Politics of the Female Body: Language and Resistance -- t2. Indigenous Third World Female Traditions of Resistance: A Recuperation of Herstories -- t3. English Education Socializing the Female Body: Cultural Alienations within the Parameters of Race, Class, and Color -- t4. Cultural “Traditions” Exiling the Female Body -- t5. Motherhood Demystified -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs it possible to simultaneously belong to and be exiled from a community? In Politics of the Female Body, Ketu H. Katrak argues that it is not only possible, but common, especially for women who have been subjects of colonial empires. Through her careful analysis of postcolonial literary texts, Katrak uncovers the ways that the female body becomes a site of both oppression and resistance. She examines writers working in the English language, including Anita Desai from India, Ama Ata Aidoo from Ghana, and Merle Hodge from Trinidad, among others. The writers share colonial histories, a sense of solidarity, and resistance strategies in the on-going struggles of decolonization that center on the body. Bringing together a rich selection of primary texts, Katrak examines published novels, poems, stories, and essays, as well as activist materials, oral histories, and pamphlets—forms that push against the boundaries of what is considered strictly literary. In these varied materials, she reveals common political and feminist alliances across geographic boundaries. A unique comparative look at women’s literary work and its relationship to the body in third world societies, this text will be of interest to literary scholars and to those working in the fields of postcolonial studies and women’s studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aCommonwealth literature (English)xWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminism and literaturexCommonwealth countries. 0aFeminism and literaturexDeveloping countries. 0aFeminism and literaturezCommonwealth countries. 0aFeminism and literaturezDeveloping countries. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aWomen and literaturexCommonwealth countries. 0aWomen and literaturexDeveloping countries. 0aWomen and literaturezCommonwealth countries. 0aWomen and literaturezDeveloping countries. 0aWomen in literaturexCommonwealth countriesxDeveloping countries. 0aWomen in literature. 0aWomenxIntellectual lifexCommonwealth countries. 0aWomenxIntellectual lifexDeveloping countries. 0aWomenzCommonwealth countriesxIntellectual life. 0aWomenzDeveloping countriesxIntellectual life. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831106886100 cprintz978081353714640uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081353930040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813539300423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813